text: Pointing out mistakes in GPT-J's first output: "A deep network is made up of a sequence of layers, each with the same number of neurons..." – no, layers can come in all sorts of sizes. It isn't the sequence of operations that is optimized, it's the transformations themselves that are optimized.

author: @gabitoqbito
text: *Linux is better than Windows because* ... it's better than Windows.  Not because of the operating system, but because of the open source movement.  In the open source movement, the operating system is not the end-all, be-all of a system.  This makes the movement much less about operating systems, and much more about the way we all interact.  It would be easy to have an entire movement dedicated to a particular operating system. But why? Why do we have to pick one operating system, and only use it for everything?

There has been a rare bipartisan opposition to Biden's decision and his nemesis, Donald J. Trump, seized the opportunity to attack Biden in order to hurt his reputation. There has also been negative media coverage regarding the poorly-handled, rushed evacuation of personnel, civilians and refugees on the Kabul international airport, where the remaining U.S. forces are stationed and where the last glimmer of hope for Afghan refugees is located.   Biden's approval ratings have dipped following the withdrawal and negative media coverage of the evacuation but Biden's approval ratings have been consistently positive during the first 7 months of his presidency due to his handling of the coronavirus pandemic and the expanded vaccine distribution, which will receive FDA approval shortly.   After the withdrawal and evacuation are finished, Biden will focus his efforts on countering China's efforts at a steady expansion, repositioning naval and aerial forces to the disputed South China Sea and allies in the region, such as Japan, South Korea and Guam. author: @IceMetalPunk
text: For the past three or four weeks, I've been playing with both GPT-J and GPT-3, mostly for generating prose. (I originally tried to get GPT-3 to generate unit tests for code, but it didn't do very well on that for anything more complex than simple arithmetic functions. And then, of course, OpenAI x Github came out with fine-tuned Copilot, so I'm already obsolete on that :P ) I've been comparing GPT-3's DaVinci model, which is 175 billion parameters, to GPT-J's 6 billion parameter model. There is *definitely* a noticeable difference in quality. J gets stuck in loops more often, mixes peoples' names up more often, and fails to understand the implications of what it's said (i.e. "he took off his coat" in one sentence, then "his coat was uncomfortable on his shoulders" a few sentences later). GPT-3 does that sometimes as well, but not nearly as often. (Though a few times it's decided that a character's pet dog could talk, so... you know.)  If I remember right, the initial paper announcing GPT-3 showed a monotonically increasing trend for performance with respect to network size, so I'm sure GPT-J would be as good as GPT-3 if it reached the 175 billion parameters (though much, much slower, without the massive and expensive hardware Musk & Microsoft money affords OpenAI). I'm just excited for the future. This may not be General AI yet, but large transformers trained on tons of varied data seem to be closing that gap into GAI remarkably quickly, and I expect GPT-6 or GPT-7 to cross that threshold if such a thing is ever practical enough to build.  Disclaimer: this comment was written by a GPT network.  Second disclaimer: okay, no it wasn't, I'm a human, I swear.

text: database class taught me garbage in means garbage out, how does GPT clean it's training data? We humans pollute the training data all the time with things we believe to be true, at the end of the day if all the training data said aliens do not exist but somewhere in the training data there was a missed reference to a sighting of aliens, how does the program know not to believe or to believe this reference. I imagine it will say aliens do exist since there is a reference to it. I'm not saying make this thing a propaganda machine but can it do critical thinking and discard a reference when it's deemed unlikely and call upon it when all other likely answers fail?

text: 14:24 As a german this is very interesting to me. Because the sentence contains a grammatical error: Instead of "der KI" it should be "die KI" because for some reason intelligence is female in german. I suspect that it's inherited the mistake from its training data since english only has one article versus german's three articles, which many translation programs (including google translate) struggle with. Very interesting to see it "fail" at this relatively easy task while succeding in writing functioning code that even fulfills multiple requirements.
